Optical Proceeding WellBut ASIC Fears Will Live On å¾®

The ASIC business takes a step back in Q3 due to customer lumpiness but should snap back in Q4. MRVL shifted to less customer specific commentary regarding its ASIC programs at its AI day and therefore didn't reiterate that its lead ASIC customer will grow in C26. While this does stoke the Alchip share loss debate, MRVL was clear that everything remains on track. For us, MSFT is a much bigger driver for the story but that is a late C26 storyline.

Making strong progress in the rest of the business with Optical performing well (guided up DD in Q3) and Carrier/Enterprise expected to be up 30%, but the focus continues to be the ASIC business,which is expected to see lumpiness in Q3. Optical strength follows similar commentary from transceiver/component providers seeing strength. Initial volume shipments for 1.6T DSPs have already begun and the stronger optical market commentary on 1.6T ramping should be a continued tailwind for the business. The big recovery in Enterprise/Carrier helps fill some of the gap with ASICs expected to snap back in Q4. While the business ex-ASIC sounded better and commentary around XPU attach is seeing continued momentum, there was little on the call to help equal the fears on the ASIC roadmap with the major customers.

**July** **Results** **In** **Line** **with** **Better** **Consumer** **Offsetting** **DC** **Revenue** **Below:** July revenue came in line with Street at $2.0B (+6% Q/Q). Data Center revenue came in worse at $1.49B (+3% Q/Q, vs St. $1.51B) with AI and cloud infrastructure now contributing over 90% of DC revenue with remaining 10% coming from on-prem. Enterprise Networking beat at $194M (+9% Q/Q, vs St. $184M) but Carrier Infrastructure below at $130M (-6% Q/Q, vs St. $147M). Consumer better at $116M (+84% Q/Q, vs St. $90M) but Automotive/Industrial slightly below at $76M (flat Q/Q, vs St. $78M). GMs reported 10bps behind at 59.4% (vs St. 59.5%) and operating margins reported in line with Street at 34.8% despite lower Opex at $493M (vs St. $497M). All in, EPS came in with Street at $0.67.

**October** **Guide** **Worse** **on** **Lumpy** **Custom** **Revenue:** October revenue guided slightly below at $2.06B (+3% Q/Q, vs St. $2.11B). By segment, Data Center expected to be flat Q/Q (vs St. +5% Q/Q) with Optical up DD % Q/Q (implies Custom down DD % Q/Q). Within DC, we are modeling ASIC -19% Q/Q, Storage +3% Q/Q, and Optical+12% Q/Q. Carrier/Enterprise in aggregate expected to grow 30% Q/Q (vs St. +6% Q/Q). Consumer guided to be down LSD % Q/Q (vs St. +4% Q/Q) as Gaming demand & seasonality continues to be the primary driver. Auto/Ind guided to $35M (vs St. +6% Q/Q) with MSD SM contribution from Auto Ethernet business. GM guided slightly better at 59.8% (vs St. 59.4%) with revenue and product mix expected to remain key determinants of GM in any given quarter.Opex guided below at $485M (vs St. $512M) driving implied OM to be slightly better at 36.0% (vs St. 35.2%). Other income and expense of $33M, tax of 10%, and shares of 870M nets EPS slightly higher at 80.74 (vs St. $0.72).

We expect significant growth in the Al business as MRVL continues to win custom ASIC business and remains the share leader in the optical DSP market, enabling the scaling of Al GPU data centers. As the general compute market begins to normalize, MRVL's legacy business should start to layer on top of the Al business that currently acts as the primary driver of the stock.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

MRVL maintains its dominant share of the optical DSP market, which continues to grow with the Al market. Ramp of ASIC business at cloud customers to reach Al revenue goal in 2025. A gradual normalization of trends in the Carrier and Enterprise end markets. Price Target: \(\) 80\$ implies 18x our CY27 EPS of \(\) 4.48\$

Continued scaling of larger and larger Al clusters increasing the demand for optical. Additional wins in switching with Hyperscale customers. Additional design wins and/or upside on current designs to support upside to Al target in 2025. A faster than expected return to the non- Al related segments of their business. Price Target: \(\) 120\$ implies 22x our CY27 EPS of \(\) 5.50\$

Share loss in the optical DSP market or the market moving towards direct drive. Slower ramp of Al ASIC wins. Slower design win momentum and slower than expected ramp in the custom ASIC business. Margin degradation from overseas competition. Price Target: \(\) 45\$ implies 15x our CY27 EPS of \(\) 3.00\$

Top Material Issues: 1) Product Design & Lifecycle: MRVL is a semis data infrastructure leader. It views its use of an advanced process technology (5nm ramping, 3nm roadmap) across its portfolio to improve product power consumption as a key differentiator. MRVL highlights that it reduced power consumption by its SSD controllers by over 40% per gigabyte using advanced process nodes and SoC architecture optimization. Its next- gen GPU product is designed to reduce power consumption by 50% vs current gen.

Company Targets: 1) Reduce power consumption by its products with each generation for set capabilities; 2) Maintain zero monetary losses as a result of legal proceedings associated with anti- competitivity behavior regulations.

Questions for Management: 1) In what engagements has MRVL seen the most traction and largest share- gain opportunities as a result of moving the portfolio to 5nm? 2) ARM processors can offer better price performance vs x86 - in what applications is ARM computing a near- term opportunity for custom segmenters with hyperscalers?
Datapoints related to AMZN 3nm design cycle and/or MSFT ASIC timing. Stronger/Weaker Al trends reflected by Hyperscale capex plans. Signs of recovery in the Enterprise and Carrier end markets.

Notable Call Details: Progressing on \(18+\) XPU socket with several already in volume production and design win pipeline at over 50 opportunities. Announced scale-up withing opportunity in UAL and Ethernet for Al workloads. Optical interconnects training traction with AEC and AOC DSPs in market and 6.4T SiPho light engines demonstrated future adoption. On- prem run rate expected to remain at around \(\) 500M\(per year. The Consumer business is expected to have a LT run rate of\) \sim \$300M/ year and the Industrial/Auto business \(\sim\) 100M/year. Demonstrated 400G per lane PAM technology which is a step towards enabling 3.2T optical interconnects. Collectively, the custom and electro- optics product lines now account for over 3/4 of total DC revenue. DC storage revenue has improved significantly reflecting a return to health in both the SSD and HDD markets. In Al and cloud switching, 12.8T products continue to ship in high volume while next- gen 51.2T switches are now ramping. Adoption is accelerating with expectation for these products to be a major driver of switch revenue growth in the next fiscal year. Recently expanded collaboration with MSFT Azure in the security market.

Marvell Tech. Marvell Technology Group Ltd. is a fabless semiconductor provider of application- specific standard products. The Company develops complex system- on- a- chip (SoC) devices using its technology portfolio of intellectual property in the areas of analog, mixed- signal, digital signal processing and embedded advanced RISC machine (ARM)- based microprocessor integrated circuits. The Company's product portfolio includes devices for data storage, enterprise- class Ethernet data switching, Ethernet physical- layer transceivers (PHY), handheld cellular, Ethernet- based wireless networking, and personal area networking.
Price Target: \(80 million 18x our CY27 EPS of\) 4.48.
Share loss in the optical DSP market or the market moving towards direct drive.
